And her daughter asks her why she chooses to be in this universe with her disappointment of a daughter if she could be anyone else, do anything else, etc. And the immigrant mother replied "no matter what, I still want to be
here with you. I will always want
to be here with you." And that was SOOO good. I sobbed because all of my life, that is all I wanted to hear. I have lived with an internal anxiety that my parents wished that their life had turned out differently. I know that they were once full of dreams, because I used to hear about those dreams all the time as a child. My mom was such a good singer, and she did really cool things with that. My dad loved boats, music, all sorts of things. But at some point, those dreams all died as the reality of the American Dream or lack thereof settled in. And it's been 25+ years of staticness. We are just a poor, immigrant family struggling to get year to year. My mom barely has friends here because she can barely speak english, and it is just so depressing. And so my entire life, I've worked so hard, studied so hard, etc. etc. at WFU on scholarship trying to become a doctor, and make a lot of money so that they don't ever feel like their sacrifices to come to America were not worth it.
